10.title: Responsibilities of foreigners, employers employing foreigners, and educational activity providers accepting foreigners
10.content:
It has been decreed that all entities receiving foreign nationals in the country for the purpose of economic activities or educational activities who entered the territory of the Czech Republic after 1July 2020 shall ensure the following for such foreign nationals:

  1. accommodation for the entire duration of their stay in the territory of the Czech Republic, including the place where the quarantine measure will be implemented, if such ameasure is ordered by aPublic Health Protection Authority;

  2. medical care or aregistering provider of medical services for the entire duration of their stay in the territory of the Czech Republic;

  3. payment for the medical care, unless the payment is secured otherwise; this does not apply to foreign nationals with along-term residence permit;

  4. their return to their country of origin if the purpose of their stay in the territory of the Czech Republic is terminated; unless is provided otherwise; this does not apply to foreign nationals with along-term residence permit;

It has been decreed that all third-country nationals shall enclose with their application for aresidence permit for the purpose of economic activities or educational activities, filed with the relevant embassy of the Czech Republic, adocument referred to in Section 31(3)(b) of Act No. 326/1999 Coll., on the Residence of Foreign Nationals in the Territory of the Czech Republic and on Amendments to Certain Acts, as amended, which will contain the obligations of the entity referred to in clause I.5 and shall enclose such adocument with their application no later than before avisa is marked in atravel document;

It has been decreed that employers and end-users of workers who are nationals of countries not on the list of countries with low risk of COVID-19 or who are nationals of the countries referred to in point III.1, who have resided for more than 12 hours in the last 14 days with the exception of those traveling with atravel agency as referred to in clause I.2(e), shall prevent the entry of these persons to all establishments and workplaces of the employer unless these persons simultaneously submit to the employer or end-user for whom they perform work the negative result of RT-PCR test for the presence of SARS CoV-2 undergone in the territory of the Czech Republic, or as referred to in clause III.5; the same obligation is applied to educational institutions in relation to students and teachers.

Full text of the measure.

11.title: Protective measure banning acceptance of visa and temporary/permanent visit requests
11.content:
It has been decreed not to receive applications for visas and temporary and permanent residence permits at the embassies of the Czech Republic in those countries that are not on the list of countries, which have alow risk of incidence of COVID-19 pursuant to Article III, with the exception of applications for:

  1. short-term seasonal work visas or short-term employment visas, provided that the foreign national will be employed in food production, health care or welfare services; or short-term work visas if they are submitted on Ukraine by Ukrainian citizens, unless the maximum of such visas set by the Ministry of the Foreign Affairs after negotiations with the Ministry of Health is exceeded,

  2. short-term visas for scientific, key and high-skilled workers, provided that the conditions defined in the Key and Scientific Staff Programme and the High-skilled Employee Programme have been met, and for critical infrastructure maintenance workers;

  3. short-term visas based on the grounds defined in clauses I.4(e) through (i);

  4. long-term seasonal work visas;

  5. special work visas;

  6. temporary residence permits, if the applications are filed by foreign nationals included in the government Programmes for Gaining Economic or Other Significant Benefits for the Czech Republic;

  7. permanent residence permits, if the applications are filed by foreign nationals included in the government programme referred to in Government Resolution No. 1014/2014;

  8. Blue card, long-term residence permits for the purpose of scientific research and applications for aresidence permit for astay over 90 days for spouses and minor children of scientists or applications for aBlue card;

  9. long-term visas and long-term residence permits for the purpose of studies;

  10. long-term or permanent residence permits for the purpose of reunification of family in the country and applications for long-term visas for family purposes, if this concerns aspouse and minor children of aforeign national with long-term or permanent residence permits for residence in the territory of the Czech Republic;

  11. along-term visa for the purpose of collecting aresidence permit in the territory of the Czech Republic;

  12. along-term visa for cultural purposes, sports-related purposes and for the purpose of asabbatical;

  13. residence permit, if the entry of these foreigners is in the interest of the Czech Republic, if the interest of the Czech Republic is supported by an appropriate document;

These exceptions only apply to applications for visas and temporary residence permits filed at the embassies of the Czech Republic in those countries where the measures implemented due to the COVID-19 pandemic allow for receiving such applications; the Ministry of Foreign Affairs will publish the list of such countries in such away that it will be possible to access the list remotely.

Full text of the measure.

12.title: Foreigner detained by the police obliged to undergo PCR test

Full text of the measure.

13.title: Protective measure allowing carrier to condition traveling to Czech Republic by fulfilling Arrival form
13.content:
International bus carriers and air transporters are to prevent those who travel from third countries or their parts that are not on the list of countries or their parts with alow risk of contagion of COVID-19 under clause III.1 and who are required to fill in the electronic form as referred to in clause I.2, from using their services, if they do not submit the certificate received on filling in the electronic form.

Full text of the measure.

14.title: Ban on free movement for people arriving from abroad
14.content:
Prohibits all persons referred to in clause I.2, including persons as referred to in clause I.2(a) through (c) and (e), from freely moving around the territory of the entire Czech Republic during their stay in the territory of the Czech Republic, or for aperiod of 10 days, or until they present the result of an RT-PCR test for the presence of SARS CoV-2 as referred to in clause I.3 or until the termination of the quarantine measure, with the exception of the following:

  1. trips to work and movement involved in performing ajob, and trips taken to perform business or other similar activities, including trips to educational institutions and any movement involved in performing this activity; this does not apply to proceedings referred to in clause I.11;

  2. trips absolutely necessary to procure basic necessities of life, to take care of children or to take care of animals; the use of necessary financial and postal services; refuelling vehicles;

  3. trips to medical facilities and welfare facilities;

  4. trips taken to take care of urgent official matters;

  5. trips back to onesplace of residence;

  6. funerals;

This prohibition does not apply to persons below the age of 5.

To foreigners referred to in clause I.11, the free movement restriction applies for aperiod of 10 days.

21.title: Mental hygiene
21.content:
Recommendations

The basic recommendations for maintaining mental health during apandemic were issued by the Association of Clinical Psychologists of the Czech Republic (in Czech).

Steps to help mental health

  1. Don'tblame yourself for feeling bad.If the situation connected with the pandemic causes you any unpleasant feelings, do not blame yourself. Apandemic is acompletely unknown situation. Such unpleasant feelings, caused in particular by great uncertainty, are completely normal and natural.
  2. Maintain relationships and social contact as you did. People naturally live in relationships - partner, family, friends. Therefore, it is not surprising that quarantine and social isolation do not benefit us. But it is these measures that are most effective in combating the pandemic. If you do not live alone, try to make the most of this time to take care of your relationships. Watch amovie together or play aboard game. To communicate with others, use all methods of long-distance communication - mobile phone, video calls, social networks, etc. If you feel lonely, it is possible that you do not even want to be in contact, because loneliness feeds on itself. In that case, acknowledge but don'tintentionally support this feeling and contact someone close to you, it will definitely help you.
  3. Hold the mode and live as "normal" as possible.Even if you work from home, try to maintain aregime similar to how you would go to work. Try to observe regular wake up time and working hours. When the days dissolve into akind of "vacuum," anxiety or remorse are far more likely to occur. In addition, aregular daily schedule gives us asense of security in an otherwise uncertain time.
  4. Don'tfocus all your attention on coronavirus only.While it is important to seek information about the current situation, it is also important to be able to turn off the media at some point. Overwhelming information can then cause feelings of anxiety. Set atime for you to read the news, e.g.30 minutes in the morning and evening.
  5. Sport benefits mental health.Exercise plays akey role in our mental well-being. Try to go for awalk every day for awhile or at least work out at home, for example, according to one of the videos of the Czech Army.
  6. Don'tbe afraid to ask for help. If you feel that the situation is affecting you and you need to confide in someone, solve aspecific problem or just talk to someone, do not hesitate to contact one of the helplines.

The article is an abbreviated version of the text Six Steps to Mental Health by Nela G.Wurmov찼, you can read the whole text.

22.title: Secondary schools
22.content:
Rules and recommendations

Based on governmental measures, in-person education in secondary schools is banned. This means that children can'tgo to school at this time. Children are being taught through distance education.

The reason is the current epidemiological situation and ahigh risk of infection. Alarge number of children meet in the classroom for arelatively long period of time, they are also in direct contact with their teachers and parents. This is associated with the risk of transmitting the infection to many contacts.

For pupils, the school will reopen on November 30th. 9th graders will go to school as usual. The rest of the pupils will rotate in between distance and in-person schooling.

23.title: After-school clubs (Dru탑iny)
23.content:
Rules and recommendations

The personal attendance of children in the after-school club is allowed for students participating in school full-time. As to say, under conditions of maintaining homogeneous groups. That means that students from other classes must not mix in the after-school club.

If the staff capacities do not allow the maintenance of homogeneous groups, it is possible to combine students from one grade in the after-school club.

An exception is made for the after-school club in schools intended for the children of employees of selected professions (e.g.health professionals), but those operate in aspecific regime.

Studentsand teachers are obliged to wear face masks in the after-school club.

24.title: Language schools
24.content:
Rules and recommendations

The personal presence of students in group lessons in language schools is prohibited. Only individual lessons(1teacher and 1student) and individual consultations are allowed.

However, groups can be taught remotely.

Participation in the state language exam is allowed for up to 10 persons. It is important to observe hygiene measures during the tests.

25.title: The travelersmap (conditions of entry into the country / obligations upon return to the Czech Republic)
25.content:
Rules and recommendations

Do you plan to travel abroad and do not know what conditions associated with measures against COVID-19 apply to you and what are your obligations after returning to the Czech Republic? Take alook at the website of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs in the so-called Traveler Map.

There you can find the country you plan to visitand see if you need to take atest before leaving, or go to the mandatory quarantine, etc. on this map. This map also contains information on the obligations arising from returning from that country. Those can include, for example, the obligation to take the COVID-19 test and have negative results, acompleted arrival form, etc.

The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Czech Republic recommends that you secure travel insurance before your trip, including medical expenses in the event of COVID-19.

Example from the Traveler'sMap Austria: As of October 31st, 2020, Austria has included the Czech Republic among the risk areas in terms of the occurrence of COVID-19. This means that from October 31st, 2020, persons arriving from the Czech Republic are obliged to submit amedically confirmed COVID-19 negative test (negative PCR test) upon entering Austria, which must not be older than 72 hours. If travelers do not have it, they must isolate themselves in suitable accommodation (at their own expense) and request aCOVID-19 test within 48 hours. In case of anegative test result, the quarantine will be terminated. Exceptions are made for commuters, commuting students, or regular family visits.

26.title: Business trips abroad
26.content:
Rules and recommendations

Measures for entrepreneurs and businessmen are different in every state. Therefore Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Czech Republic has launched anew free service that will help Czech companies with visas even where countries do not currently issue the necessary documents. The service also helps with exceptions from mandatory quarantine for business trips abroad or the arrival of akey business partner from acountry where it is not currently possible to travel to the Czech Republic.

Entrepreneurs can send questions and requests for help at obchodnicesty@mzv.cz. The request should include contact information for you and your key partners so that the Ministry can get in touch with them. By default, they should do so within 12 hours of receiving the inquiry.

Details on the assistance from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs.

27.title: Airports
27.content:
Before departure

Firstly, find out what rules apply to you before entering aforeign country (e.g.PCR test, quarantine, etc.) on the Traveler'sMap. Also, check the current hygiene measures at the airport (V찼clav Havel Airport).

Returning to the Czech Republic

Upon arrival look at the following map to discover the list of countries and the measures that applyafter returning, varying according to the degree of risk of infection.

  1. All passengers arriving from acountry that is not on the list of countries with alow risk of COVID-19 disease must fill in the arrival formbefore their departure to the Czech Republic.
  2. After sending the completed information, the passenger will receive aconfirmation e-mail with aQR code and alink.
  3. The form can be printed or displayed on amobile device and presented at the passport border control upon arrival in the Czech Republic.

For foreigners

It ispossible to travel to the Czech Republiconly in strictly necessary cases, such aswork- orbusiness-relatedtrips (including commuters), trips motivated by family necessities and medicalreasons.

Insurance

The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Czech Republic recommends that you secure travel insurance before your trip, including medical expenses in the event of COVID-19.

Czech airports like transit airports

All information for EU citizens and citizens of other countries can be found in this table.

Transit airports outside the Czech Republic

If you are traveling abroad and you have to change trains during your flight, look at the Traveler'smap. The rules for transit should be written here. If this information is not explicitly written on the given page, contact the info line of the Ministry: +420 224 183 200 (available on MON-FRI from 08:00 - 16:00).

28.title: Slovakia
28.content:
Rules and recommendations

People arriving in Slovakia from the Czech Republic must have anegative PCR test max. 72 hours old. As an alternative, they canregister via the e-border form, enter domestic quarantine, and get tested at least 5daysafter the arrival.

Exceptions to the above quarantine, registration, and test obligations apply to:

  • drivers of haulage, bus and rail transport;
  • with the consent of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Slovak Republic, persons arriving for the purpose of acute diagnosis and treatment, incl. people close to them;
  • citizens of the EU Member States and their family members transiting through the territory of Slovakia to another EU Member State (transit means atransit for amaximum of 8hours without stopping, except for refueling; this exception also applies when changing means of transportation, e.g.for arrival after country to and from the international airport);
  • people coming for the purpose of enforcing acourt decision in the matter of parents' alternating care for minor children;
  • employees of operators of critical infrastructure elements in the energy and industry sectors;
  • cross-border workers up to adistance of 30 km from an open border crossing point;
  • people with apermanent or temporary residence permit in the Czech Republic who are studying in Slovakia or going to take entrance exams to study, incl. one accompanying person;
  • persons with apermanent or temporary residence permit in the states neighboring Slovakia, who come to Slovakia due to urgent care for close family members, incl. one accompanying person;
  • persons with apermanent or temporary residence permit in the Czech Republic who manage land on the territory of Slovakia at adistance of max. 10 km from the state border;
  • persons coming from the Czech Republic for the purpose of production of an audiovisual work, submission of an artistic performance, or realization of awork of art.

For the return from Slovakia, which is currently on the list of so-called "red states", apply the following measure: Return from abroad from aplace with ahigher risk of infection (CZ N찼vrat ze zahrani챠 zm챠sta svy큄큄챠m rizikem n찼kazy).

Before entering the Czech Republic, passengers must fill in an arrival form and pass aPCR test or go to quarantine. However, there are several exceptions that you will find in the measure above or on the web page of the Ministry of interior affairs.

More details can be found here.

Current measures in Slovakia.

29.title: Means of transport
29.content:
Recommendations and Regulations

It is essential to protect yourself and others while using public transport.

The obligation to wear aface mask needs to be followed while travelling via any public transport, including bus/tram stops, train platforms and waiting rooms. Please keep your mouth and nose covered before arriving into these waiting areas.

Please keep social distancing. You should social distance before you get on public transport, and also while travelling via public transport if possible. If not necessary, please do not touch any surfaces inside public transport (especially handles or rails) as many people will have touched these areas before. For extra protection, you can use gloves disposable gloves (rubber or plastic gloves), and also textile gloves (we recommend to wash these after arriving home).

While travelling via public transport, there is alarge turnover of people. Therefore please use enhanced hygiene measures. If possible, avoid travelling via public transport, e.g.walk to your workplace or to the shop. You will get some fresh air, and you will also reduce the risk of infection.

30.title: Elementary art schools
30.content:
Rules and recommendations

Personal presence of pupils in elementary arts-based schools is prohibited.

Exceptions are individual consultations or teaching (only one pupil, one teacher and event. legal representative).

As for singing, it is an activity in which there is an increased spread of droplets, and therefore joint singing of more than 5people is prohibited inside. Even if theyexercise their profession. However, kindergartens and home residences have an exception to this ban (so you sure can sing at home).

31.title: High schools
31.content:
Rules and recommendations

Osobn챠 p챠tomnost 탑찼k킁 na v첵uce stedn챠ch큄kol se pro vt큄inu ron챠k킁 zakazuje.V첵jimku maj챠 큄koly z챠zen챕 Ministerstvem spravedlnosti a큄koly z챠zen챕 pi za챠zen챠ch pro v첵kon 첬stavn챠 v첵chovy nebo ochrann챕 v첵chovy.

Prezenn mohou v첵uku tak챕 nav큄tvovat탑찼civoboru vzdl찼n챠 Praktick찼 큄kola jednolet찼 aPraktick찼 큄kola dvoulet찼.

D찼le prob챠h찼 v첵uka prezenn pro탑찼kyz찼vren첵ch ron챠k킁 a탑찼kytvrt첵ch ron챠k킁 큄estilet첵ch vzdl찼vac챠ch program킁 vkonzervatoi.

Povolen찼 je tak챕 praxeza p챠tomnosti nejv첵큄e 20 탑찼k킁 nebo student킁. Umo탑nno je tak챕 praktick챕vyuov찼n챠 apraktick찼p챠prava탑찼k킁 astudent킁 zdravotnick첵ch obor킁 ve zdravotnick첵ch za챠zen챠ch aza챠zen챠ch soci찼ln챠ch slu탑eb.

Povoleny jsouindividu찼ln챠 konzultace pro v큄echny studenty a탑찼ky (pouze jeden 탑찼k nebo student ajeden pedagogick첵 pracovn챠k).

D찼le se povoluje kon찼n챠 z찼vren첵ch zkou큄ek, maturitn챠ch zkou큄ek, absolutori챠 amezin찼rodn uzn찼van첵ch zkou큄ek.

Prezenn챠 v첵uka mus챠 prob챠hat vnemnn첵ch t챠d찼ch, oddlen챠ch nebo skupin찼ch 탑찼k킁 nebo student킁. D찼le je teba dodr탑ovat ve큄ker찼 hygienick찼 opaten챠. Pedev큄챠m pak m챠t zakryt찼 첬sta anos rou큄kou.

D킁vodem je souasn찼 epidemiologick찼 situace avysok챕 riziko n찼kazy. Ve 큄kole se setk찼v찼 velk챕 mno탑stv챠 탑찼k킁 na pomrn dlouhou dobu, d찼le jsou vkontaktu suiteliadoma pak srodii. St챠m je spojen챕 riziko penosu n찼kazy na mnoho kontakt킁.

32.title: Vocational schools
32.content:
Rules and recommendations

The personal presence of the secondary vocational schools students and vocational school students is prohibited for most grades. Schools established by the Ministry of Justice and schools working alongside establishments for institutional and preventative children'scare are exempt.

Students of vocational schools (one year and two year course) can also attend classes in person.

Furthermore, teaching takes place in person for final-year students and fourth-year students of six-year educational programs at the conservatory.

Practical education in the presence of amaximum of 20 pupils or students is allowed. It also enables practical teaching and practical training of students of medical disciplines in medical facilities and social services facilities.

Individual consultations are also allowed (only one student and one teacher).

Furthermore, final examinations, school-leaving examinations, graduations and internationally recognized examinations are permitted.

Full-time teaching must take place in assigned classes, departments or groups of students. In addition, all hygienic measures must be observed. Above all, you have to wear aface mask.

The reason for these measures is the current epidemiological situation and the high risk of infection. At school, alarge number of pupils meet for arelatively long time, they are also in contact with teachers and at home with their relatives. This is associated with the risk of transmitting the infection.

33.title: Higher Vocational Schools
33.content:
Rules and recommendations

The personal presence of college students is prohibited, with afew exceptions.

Schools established by the Ministry of Justice and schools working alongside establishments for institutional and preventative children'scare are exempt.

Furthermore, teaching takes place in person for final year students.

It is allowed for high school students to attend practical classes and practical training in the presence of amaximum of 20 students. It also enables practical teaching and practical training for students of medical disciplines in medical facilities and social service facilities.

Individual consultations are also allowed (only one pupil or student and one teacher).

In addition, the realization of final exams, graduations and internationally recognized exams is permitted.

Full-time teaching must take place in assigned classes, departments or groups of students. In addition, all hygienic measures must be observed. Above all, do not forget to wear face masks.

The reason for these measures is the current epidemiological situation and the high risk of infection. At school, alarge number of students meet for arelatively long time, they are also in contact with teachers and at home with their relatives. This is associated with the risk of transmitting the infection.

34.title: Maturita exam
34.content:
Rules and recommendations

Personal presence of students at the exam is allowed.All hygienic measures must be observed during the test.

There are no changes to the form of the Maturitaexam yet. This may change according to how theepidemiological situation developsWe will update the information in the case of change. You also need to follow the information provided by your educational institution.

The final years of secondary schools can now prepare for the Maturitaexam in person.

If you need psychological help or advice on coping with stress, read more in the Stress and Pandemic Impact Management section.

35.title: Final exams
35.content:
Rules and recommendations

No form of final exams has been determined yet. Right now it is assumed that the exams will go forward as usual, with in-person attendance of students at the exam.

This could change based on the epidemiological situation. If any changes occur, you will be informed in advance on this page.

It is also important to monitor the latest information given by your school. Specifically the information from the academic department related to the date and form of the exams and the hygienic regulations surrounding them. Also, check the school website.

At the present time, students are preparing for their exams through distance education, since in-person education is not allowed. This ban also applies to practical education, with the exception of medical specializations who will continue in practical education.

We are all going through adifficult time right now, if you need any psychological help or tips on how to cope with stress, look in the section on Stress and handling the impact of the pandemic.

36.title: eNeschopenka
36.content:
Rules and recommendations

eNeschopenka is asick leave (reporting incapacity to work) for the employer and the social security administration, which is issued electronically by adoctor.

The purpose of the eNeschopenka is to simplify the transfer of information, as it connects electronically three different entities doctors, employers and the Czech Social Security Administration (SSZ).

eNeschopenka refers to the temporary incapacity to work. In practice, it means that the employee does not have to carry physical paper documents anywhere it can be handled online remotely, from home and without the risk of getting infected. The employee will receive acertificate of incapacity to work which can be useful in the case of an inspection of the competent authorities.

37.title: Proms
37.content:
Rules and recommendations

School dances (e.g.maturitn챠 plesy aka proms) are not allowed to happen in public or in private. Social events of any kind are not allowed, and school dances and other cultural events fall under this rule.

38.title: Entrance exams
38.content:
Rules and recommendations

At the moment, it is assumed that the entrance exams will take place the normal way, i.e.in the personal presence of students.

This may change as the epidemiological situation develops /keeps developing. You will be informed about the change on time on this website.

You should also keep track of the information provided by the school you are applying to. Especially information from the studentdepartment, specifically on the dates, form of entrance exams and hygienic measures.

We are all going through difficult times now. If you need psychological help or advice on coping with stress, look into theStress and Pandemic Impact Management

39.title: Mental hygiene of frontline workers
39.content:
Recommendations

The basic recommendations (in Czech) for maintaining mental health during apandemic were issued by the Association of Clinical Psychologists of the Czech Republic.

Special crisis lines have also been set up for paramedics and other front-line workers:

  • COLLEGIAL SUPPORT LINE for healthcare workers: 607 400 591, 720 219 618
  • SOCIAL CLINICS: PSYCHOLOGICAL ASSISTANCE FOR ASSISTING PROFESSIONS (doctors, health professionals, social workers, teachers, hygienists, firefighters, and police officers, etc.): 733 644 268 or online:https://www.socialniklinika.cz
  • Support and supervision #dl찼mcom킁탑u: 116 123

40.title: Workplace
40.content:
Recommendations and Regulations

Obligation to cover your mouth and nose especially with aface mask, arespirator or ascarf applies also in workplaces.

Within the obligation of wearing aface mask while working in workplaces, some people may have an exemption. This includes nursery teachers, health workers if it is necessary to perform thefirst aid (e.g.resuscitation), public transport drivers, judges, advocates, prosecutors, experts and interpreters during the trials, performers, hosts, news readers, and persons who work with heat within the 3rd and the 4th burden degree (glassmakers, metallurgist etc.).

You can also remove your face mask if you work in one place and when there are no colleagues or other people within the safe distance of at least 2m away from you (both conditions need to be met at the same time). E.g.while being alone in your office at least 2m away from other people the face mask can be removed. Please wear your face mask in all other circumstances.

If possible, please work from home. Workplaces are one of the most common settings where people get infected by COVID-19. If it is impossible for you to work from home, please wear aface mask and follow basic hygiene measures.

41.title: State exams
41.content:
Rules and recommendation

State final exams are conducted as usual, thus in-personattendance of students atthe exam.

Currently, the in-person attendance is allowed up to 10 people (inc. examiners). The obligation to keep increased hygiene rules arestill valid. This fact may change due to the evolution of epidemiologicalsituation. You will be informed about possible changes in timehere on this website.

It is also necessary to follow information that isbeing provided by your school. Primarily information from study affairs office, mainly because of terms, forms of state exam and hygiene measures.

Primarily, directyour questions to study affairs office or academicsenate. Also follow websites of university or faculty.

We are all going throughharsh times. If you need apsychologicalhelp oran advice,how to deal with stress, take alook to the thread Stress pandemic impact management.

42.title: Skin problems
42.content:
Recommendations and Regulations

Wearing aface mask maycause skin problemsor worsen skin conditions, especially to those who already suffer from some skin conditionsuch as acne, eczema, or rosacea.

If you suffer from any of the skin conditions stated above due to wearing aface mask, please try face masks made out of different materials.

It is important to follow the correct hygiene routine while using face coverings make sure to change your disposable face masks regularly and disinfect your reusable face masks thoroughly and regularly. Here is how to take care of your face mask.

It is also important to wash your face regularly and to use asuitable face moisturizer. If your skin condition does not get better, or it worsens, please contact your dermatologist who should be able to find the right solution for you. Thanks to new technologies, there are many gentle materials such as nanomaterials. These materials can be worn even by people with sensitive skin. Face masks help us to reduce spreading of the virus, it is vital to protect ourselves by wearing them.

43.title: School canteens
43.content:
Rules and recommendation

Operation of school canteens is permitted.Pupils who attend in-person tuition and school staff present at aworkplace may use canteens.

Other pupils and school staff who did not attend school for tuition may pick up meals at thedispensingwindow.We recommend that those pupils will not mix with pupils attending tuition in-person.

Keeping increased hygiene measures in catering facilities are condition for operation:

  • Pupils and staff are obliged to wear veilsinschool canteens, which can be taken off only during consumption.
  • Up to 4peoplecan sit at one table
  • Tables mustbe at least 1,5mapart
  • In the canteen can not be more people than seats.
  • It is necessary to keep sufficient distances between various classes.

Public can not consume atschool canteens

44.title: Staff training
44.content:
Recommendations

The general hygiene rules at the workplace apply to the various necessary trainings (eg health and safety training).

All training is recommended to take placeonline.

45.title: Company canteens
45.content:
Rules and recommendations

Company catering is an exception to the ban on being present in catering services (it can also be prison canteens or providers of health and social services). However, government action has several rules:

  • customers are seated so that there is adistance of at least 1.5meters between them (this does not apply if they are sitting at one table),
  • amaximum of 4people can sit at one table (except for household members), if it is along table, there must be adistance of at least 2meters between the groups (the exception is again household members),
  • the operator will not allow more customers in the interior than there are customer seats,
  • the operator is obliged to record in writing the total current number of seats for customers,
  • in the case of persons who consume food and meals outside the catering establishment, but in its proximity (e.g.the dispensing window), the distance between persons must be at least 2meters, unless they are household members,
  • for hygienic reasons, it is recommended to use non-cash payments as amatter of priority,
  • the operator must also ensure the possibility of hand disinfection when entering indoor and outdoor areas.

Customers must be encouraged by information materials to maintain adistance in the queues of at least 2meters.

46.title: Schools defined in 짠 16 of Act 561/2004 Coll.
46.content:

47.title: Purpose of the measures
47.content:
What is the purpose of the measures?

The purpose of the governmental measures is to reduce the reproductive number of COVID-19 to such an extent, that the health care system of the Czech Republic can manage the epidemic and not have to limit care for patients in order to increase the number of available hospital beds for those with COVID-19.

Flattening the curve will give the healthcare system time to care for patients with COVID-19.

The next step is to bring the COVID-19 epidemic under control, that is, to prevent the so-called community-based spread of the disease. Each of us can individually contribute to reducing the Rnumberby respecting all hygiene recommendations and limiting contact with other people.

Please follow all of the hygienic measures, especially: wearing your mask, disinfecting your hands, and social distancing.

48.title: State of Emergency
48.content:
State of Emergency

The state of emergency is one of the extraordinary measures of the Constitutional Act on the Security of the Czech Republic. It is announced by the government.

One of the cases in which the government can declare astate of emergency is in the situation when there is adangerous or significant threat to our lives or health. And this is the current case.

The government can declare astate of emergency for amaximum of 30 days. However, this situation may be extended with the prior consent of the Chamber of Deputies.

The state of emergency ends with the expiration of the period for which it was declared or with adecision to cancel it. The Government or the Chamber of Deputies can cancel the state of emergency.

Crisis measures

These are measures intended to eliminate or ease the consequences of these difficult times.

The implementation of acrisis measure can restrict certain rights and freedoms and impose specific obligations. Crisis measures may be issued by the government in the event of adeclared state of emergency based onthe law on Crisis Management and on the Amendment of Certain laws (Crisis Act).

The effectivenessof crisis measures was prolongedfor the duration of the state of emergency.

49.title: School counseling facilities
49.content:
Rules and recommendations

School counseling services can continue to work without restrictions. It is, however, necessary to follow all hygienic regulations. It is essential to cover anose and mouthwhen in contact with people in person.

We do not recommendto take part in group activities. It could increase the risk of infection as this would put the participants and their loved ones at risk.

Some schools offer the services of school psychologists alongside the school counselors.The current situation can take atoll on one'smental health, so do not hesitate to ask for help. If you do not know whether your school offers the services of apsychologist, reach out to your teachers. You can also look for advice in theStress and handlingimpacts of the pandemicsection.

50.title: School accommodation facilities
50.content:
Rules and recommendations

Due to the uncertain pandemic situation, it is prohibited to offer any accommodation in educational dormitories and hallsto any students who live on adifferent address within the grounds of the Czech Republic. This also applies to the university students.

There aresome exemptions. Students ofthe sameclassand practical trainingcan stay at theschool accommodationfacilities. The exemption also applies to allstudents of medicineand educationwith practical training, and to students with an obligation to work.

Dormitories and halls of residence canbe used by PhDstudents.

My residential address is at adormitory/hall

Students who do not have another residential address within the grounds of the Czech Republicmay remain in dormitories/halls of residence. The residential address is aplace which is considered to be your permanent place to live, aplace where it feels like home to you. If you provide aconsent in which you state the dormitory/hall of residence, not any other place, is ahome to you, you may remain living there.

If you stay in adormitory/hall of residence, please maintain increased hygiene measures (the rule of 3: face mask hands social distancing).

However, the Ministry of Education is asking, if possible, for students to return home andthus reducing their social contacts. Universities decide on the details of the operation of the dormitories independently. If you have any questions, please contact the dormitory operator directly.

If this measure may cause you getting into adifficult social situation, please contact your school as universities may help their students via social scholarships. Financial help is also offered by the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.

51.title: Infected member of the household
51.content:
Recommendations

If possible, designate aseparate room for an infected member of the household. If you cannot designate aseparate room, then it is important the beds in the room are at least one meter apart and the place is regularly ventilated.

The infected person must follow isolation rules, you must quarantine.

To minimise the risk of transmitting the infection to other members of the household, the infected person is advised to move around the common areas of the house in aface mask. The infected person should always go to the bathroom as the last one and should use his/her own towel. The use of waste is also important. Used face masks, respirators or disposable gloves must be placed in aspecial bag and separated from the rest of your waste. Detailed instructions can be found on the website of the Ministry ofEnvironment.

52.title: Support and delivery services to risk groups and those infected
52.content:
Rules and recommendations

All types of delivery services and neighborhood help are an exception to the restrictions on the free movement of people.

However, it is necessary to follow basic hygiene rules. Volunteers must be equipped with protective equipment (face masks, goggles, gloves) and must not come into direct contact with an infected person or aperson from arisk group.

Any items or food that the volunteer distributes should be left in front of the house (on the door handle of the front of the door) or another accessible place. In return, the person for whom the purchase was made leaves the money in front of the door or transfers it to abank account.

There are several voluntary initiatives that you can turn to at any time for help. These are, for example, Helping Neighbors or the Neighborhood Assistance initiative.

53.title: Operation of Offices
53.content:
Rules and recommendations

Office hours are limited to 2days aweek for 5hours. You can find the opening hours for each Office on the official board of the given office, which is placed by the office building entrance.

Written and/or telephone contact is preferable over apersonal visit to the office. This will help reduce the risk of infection to you and those around you.

You can also set up adata-box free of charge for online communication with the authorities. The data-box can be set up at any CzechPoint branch. If you have an e-ID (eObanka), you can set up adata box online.

Only necessary matters should be handled in person. If you go to the office in person, it is necessary to have afacemask at all times, disinfect your hands and keep your distance. Keep adistance not only when in the queue but also when communicating with the officials.

It is good to first call the office before the visit to find out if it is necessary for you to go to the office physically, and possibly arrange aspecific date of the visit. This will avoid risky waiting in aqueue.

Send all documents by mail beforehand.

Increased hygienic measures must be observed by the employees of the office among themselves. More information can be found on this website.

54.title: ID Exchange
54.content:
Rules and recommendations

If your driving license or professional driver'squalification license has expired during the state of emergency, you do not need to change it, as it is still considered valid. You can only renew an expired driver'slicense after the state of emergency has ended.

This does not apply to other licenses (such as an identity card) and you must renew their validity even in astate of emergency. After aprevious telephone or e-mail agreement, the given Office will allow you to arrange the exchange of the document in person. Details More details on the issuance of documents and the opening hours of Offices can be found on the website of the Ministry of the interior of the Czech Republic.

You can find the answers to the questions related to the exchange of licenses in the section Operation of Offices.

55.title: Notaries, lawyers, executors
55.content:
Rules and Recommendations

The general ban on service providers does not apply to lawyers, notaries, or executors. You can continue to use their services, upon agreement with their office.

Lawyers, notaries, and executors can issue their specific measures, so contact them directly for more detailed information.

56.title: Household (shopping, repairs etc.)
56.content:
Rules and recommendations

Shopping

For details on how stores work, please see Shops and Services > Retail.

Repairs

For details onthe operation of services and repairs, please seeShops and Services > Repairs and Services.

Craftsmen

Craftspeople can still visit and work in households, as government measures apply only to performing services in the store. However, please try to use their services only when necessary. You should postpone minor repairs.

During their visit, it is necessary to follow hygienic measures. Everyone present should wear aface mask and keep adistance from each other.

Use your own pen for signing, and if possible, prefer non-cash payment (transfers, card payments, etc.). Cash circulates in the hands of avast number of people every day. By choosing contactless payments, you can help reduce the risk of infection.

If someone from your household is in quarantine or isolation, it is necessary to cancel the visit of acraftsman. In the event of an emergency where the repair cannot be postponed, you must inform the craftsman about the presence of infected person prior to the visit. Infected person should not meet the craftsman under any circumstances.

57.title: STK
57.content:
Rules and recommendations

STK (vehicle inspection) remains in operation. You can still book technical inspections. Please remember that driving without avalid SKT is aminor offense even in times of astate of emergency.

58.title: Pets
58.content:
Rules and recommendations

Animals and Covid-19

There are rare cases where pets had been infected by COVID-19. So far, we have limited information about the effects of this disease on animals, so treat your pet like any other member of the household. If there is an infected person in your house, reduce the contact between the infected and the animal to aminimum.

Remember, that virus can be transmitted on the animal'sfur, so wash and disinfect your hands thoroughly before and after contact with the animal. Do not let strangers stroke your pet.

Visits to the vet

Before the visit, always call the veterinarian and consult with him whether your appointment is necessary. Stay in the waiting room only for the inevitable time and keep atwo-meters distance from other people in the room. Wearing aface mask is amust. Try to avoid touching objects that had been touched by people before you, such as handles or railings.

Always inform your veterinarian if you think you have met an infected or quarantined person!

Walking the dog

There is an exception to the curfew for dog walking - you can walk your dog even after 11PM, but only within 500 meters from your house or flat. During the day (5AM - 10.59 PM), you can walk your dog anytime without restrictions. However, always wear your face mask and keep atwo-meters distance from others.

Walking the dog in isolation or quarantine

If you have to quarantine or go to isolation, you should ask someone to walk your dog for you. During the transmission, please pay extra attention to hygiene measure - wear aface mask or respirator, ideally put on gloves and wash and disinfect your hands thoroughly before and after.

The quarantined or isolated person can only walk the dog when there is no one else to do it for him/her. If this situation occurs, please take your dog out only for the necessary time. When staying outside, avoid places with ahigher concentration of people, wear aface mask and keep atwo-meters distance.

59.title: Execution of the sentence imprisonment
59.content:
Rules and recommendations

In astate of emergency visits to prisons, remand prisons, and security detention facilities are prohibited. The ban is compensated by extending apossibility to have acall for 30 minutes per day. Also, prisoners are allowed to have avideocalls with their loved ones.

Lawyers can go to prisons on behalf of clients. However, they must face masks in all of the areas of the facility, including dealings with the client. Lawyers can also communicate with clients online using the "Skype Defense" program.

60.title: Testing
60.content:
Ananochip being placed while testing

Hoax

While being tested ananochip is placed inside the person being tested.

The whole content(in Czech).

Explanation

The picture that usually accompanies this hoax is actually amicrochip that has the whole Bible saved on it. This article was published in 2009.

Explanation of the whole hoax (in Czech).

Article from 2009.

Explanation of how the sample for testing is taken.

The testing sets contain vaccines and damage the brain membrane.

Hoax

The meaning of the vaccine is allegedly to gain control over people through the vaccination or to infect people with Covid-19 through the vaccine. Another problem of the test is allegedly that it damages the membrane of the brain.

This hoax has been spread in many different forms across social media, mainly in misinformation groups.

Explanation

Similar hoaxes have been appearing since spring not only in the Czech republic, but across the whole world. According to experts this is an absolutely nonsensical claim. Being tested can in no possible way damage the blood-brain barrier. Tests from the nasopharynx have been conducted for decades and it is not something new connected to the new coronavirus. It is also nonsense that anything would be placed in the nasopharynx using the testing kit, as they are sterile.

An explanation of the whole hoax (in Czech).Another explanation(in Czech).

Other similar hoaxes(in Czech).

Fake numbers from testing places

Hoax

There are 138 testing places in the Czech republic, each of them does 4-6 tests in an hour. In 8hours that'samaximum of 46 tests in aday, multiply that by 138 and you get 6624 tests per day. And now aquestion, where do these 33 000 daily tests come from?

Explanation

There are alot of factual mistakes in this statement.

There are currently over 170 testing places in the Czech republic and new ones are being added. The complete list of testing places can be found on the website of the Ministry of Education.

Another mistake is that they only complete 4-6 tests in aday. It is possible to book aspot in advance in most places and they can manage tens of tests in an hour. If we say that they do 30 tests in an hour (one every two minutes) and multiply that by the 170 testing sites, the result is 40 800 daily tests, which is approximately the capacity of testing places in Czech republic.

Explanation of the whole hoax (in Czech).

61.title: Penalties - Business
61.content:
Regulations

Wearing aface mask

The extraordinary measures issued by the Ministry of Health the state obligation to wear aface mask. Afine of up to CZK 10,000 can be imposed on the spot for violating these measures. Afine can be imposed on the spot or the matter can be referred to administrative proceedings. You can find the rules on face masks in the Face mask section.

The penalties are governed by this legislation

Penalties result from Act No. 258/2000 Sb., on the protection of public health (짠 92n (1) (b) of this Act) and Act No. 250/2016 Sb. on the liability for offenses and proceedings concerning them (짠 91 of this Act).

Violation of the governmental crisis measures

Most of the current restrictions fall under the crisis measures of the government and violating them could lead to afine of up to CZK 20,000.

The penaltiesare governed by this legislation

The penalties result from Act No. 240/2000 Sb., on Crisis Management and Amendments to Certain Acts (Crisis Act) (짠 34 (1) (a) of this Act).

62.title: The government is watching your phones
62.content:
The government is watching your phones

Hoax

The government is monitoring the ban on free movement and gathering through mobile operators.

Explanation

This hoax is connected to the creation of the Smart quarantine. As apart of this it was possible to install two applications- eRou큄ka and Mapy.cz. If you agreed the hygienics were able to find people you came into contact with and where you were. This option completely disappeared in the eRou큄ka 2.0version, which is now completely anonymous.

Another way to help with tracing is to provide the data from your phone from the last 5days to create aso called memory map, which will help the infected person better determine their contacts that they met with and remember where they were. This information cannot be accessed without your consent.

Any monitoring of citizens without them being directly aware of it is impossible. The mobile operator can only share this information with the security forces upon your request.

Sources (in Czech)

Tracing with the help of mobile phones.

Is there any reason to be afraid of the Smart quarantine?

Hoax: the eRou큄ka app is used to watch citizens.

63.title: Post Office
63.content:
Rules and recommendations

Post offices remain open. However, they operate in alimited regime. Overview of post offices opening hours is available here. Moreover, you can still use Czech POINT service at the specific post office.

Please wear aface mask and keep spacing during avisit to the post office. Use your face mask also during atakeover in case of home delivery. If you know your signature is/might be needed, take your own pen.

The post office is not obliged to follow limitations on the number of people but has to manage all the hygiene standards. The number of people allowed to enter can differ from one branch office to another.

Please disinfect your hands before entering the building or receiving the delivery at home. We advise you to open your package outdoor to minimize the risk of infection.

Delivery process

Home delivery remains without limitation. If the consignee is not present by the time of the delivery, the package will be stored at the post office and available to pick up. The storage time of shipments has been extended 30 days for letters, 15 days for parcels.

For higher safety, we advise using contactless delivery via special code.

If you need to pick up delivery while in quarantine or self-isolation, please do inform specific post office branch. In this case, the special rules of delivery for quarantined or isolated persons will be applied.

Stored parcels with identification code will be passed to the person with valid identification code together with the name and surname of the consignee (resp. delivery number). This procedure is not possible in case of to the attention of delivery.

64.title: Constructions and reconstructions
64.content:
Rules and recommendations

Constructions and reconstructions can continue. Craftspeople can come to your house as government restrictions apply only to performing services in the store. However, if you meet with workers, it is necessary to follow hygiene measures.

During the visit, everyone present should wear aface mask and keep adistance. If possible, prefer non-cash payment (transfers, card payments, etc.).

You can also build ahouse with self-help. Volunteering and neighbourhood assistance are allowed for urgent and necessary actions. Nevertheless, please do not abuse the rules and think about the protection of you and others. Avoid clustering of people and follow hygienic measures.

65.title: Wearing masks is bad for your health
65.content:
Hoax:

Different variations of the statement: Face masks are bad for your immune system. Bacteria multiply in face masks. Face masks cause diseases. The WHO did not initially recommend the use of face masks. "

Explanation:

There is currently no evidence that wearing face masks weakens the immune system in any way. It is also nonsense that CO2 would accumulate under the face mask and harm us. The CO2 molecules are so small that it is no problem for them to go through the mask. Only bacteria that you exhale yourself will stay inside the mask. If you use it properly and wash or boil it after each use, there can be no significant multiplication of bacteria.

Nor is there any evidence that the masks can cause any diseases. The only possible health problem caused by wearing amask may be an allergic reaction of the skin to the material from which the face mask is made (if you suffer from such an allergy).

Yes, the WHO did not recommend the use of face masks in the first wave. But it was not because it was ineffective, but for fear of misuse. When used and worn properly, face masks are an effective protection against the sprea of coronavirus according to the WHO.

Here is an explanation of the whole hoax (in Czech)

or here.

66.title: Recommendations for landlords
66.content:
Recommendations

If you need to discuss the urgent matter with your tenant, please favour acall or other form of online communication.

Ask for acontactless rent.

Please be more thoughtful with the tenants in this crisis. For example, moving in or out is now risky. If possible, postpone tenants moving to better, less infectious time.

67.title: Shopping
67.content:
Rules and recommendations

It is necessary to wear aface mask throughout the time you are in the store and to keep distancing from other customers (especially in the queue before checkout). Before entering the store, please disinfect your hands carefully. Please repeat this after returning home. If you prefer higher protection, we advise you to wear gloves. Do not touch the things in the store unnecessarily, pick up pastries, fruits, and vegetables exclusively in gloves or use aplastic bag to pick up it.

If you feel endangered by the disease or currently in quarantine/self-isolation, ask for help with shopping your relatives or neighbours. If they are unable or busy to do it, do not hesitate to ask volunteers. They will be happy to help you. You can also shop online and get your purchase delivered to your doorstep.

You can visit ashopping mall in agroup of 6people at most with avalid exception for families. The store must guarantee at least 15 m짼 of space per customer. In stores smaller than 15 m짼 this restriction does not apply to children under 15 and people with disabilities. In stores bigger than 15 m짼, children under 6with acompany of adult person are excluded.

Apriority entrance is ensured for persons with disability to prevent them from waiting in long queues. Store staff is not permitted to request usage of ashopping cart in case of individuals with baby-carriage, the baby in baby-carriage is exempt from limits on the number of allowed people in the store.

The sales area, defined for the purposes of restricting the number of people, means the store area accessible to customers including changing rooms, area behind sales counters used by cashier/seller. Store offices and warehouses are not included. It is also mandatory to adopt regime and organizational measures and queue management (in front of and in the shop).

It is also mandatory to adopt regime and organizational measures and queue management (in front of and in the shop).

Try to use primarily e-shops. If visiting ashop is necessary, please pay increased attention to hygiene, keep spacing and use contactless payment. We know that shopping is avery common activity. However, alot of people gathers there, so please be careful and responsible. By respecting these rules, you help us to protect you and other people.

68.title: Football
68.content:
Rules and recommendations

Currently, the number of people for outdoor sports is limited to 6max. This means that you can play football outside, but there must be no more than 6people on the field (typically two teams of 3). Amateur football competitions are not allowed. The only exception is professional athletes. You can learn more about the rules of playing professional football including public participation in the Sports Events section.

69.title: Disinfection
69.content:
Rules and recommendations

How to make adisinfectant gel?

You can usually get the ingredients in apharmacy or drugstore. They are exempt from the ban on shops being open.

What you need:

  • pure alcohol, i.e.96% ethanol or 99.8% isopropyl alcohol (you can buy it in adrugstore or paint and varnish shop)
  • 3% hydrogen peroxide (which you can buy in apharmacy)
  • 98% glycerol (also called glycerin; available in apharmacy)
  • sterilised or boiled water (you can prepare it at home)
  • aclean and sterilised container with alid
  • ameasuring cup, asyringe (it will make your work easier, but you can do it without it)

Process:

Prepare 833 ml of alcohol (or 752 ml of isopropyl alcohol) and pour it into acontainer with acapacity of at least one litre. Slowly mix in 42 ml of hydrogen peroxide and stir it well. Then add 15 ml of glycerol- it is better to use asyringe for this, as it has avery thick consistency, and without the syringe, it is hard to measure the dosage. Then add boiled water so the level reaches 1l, close the container and shake it well. At this point, you can pour it into smaller containers that you can carry it with you. The final product should sit for three days, but if it is necessary, you can use it straight away as it works immediately.

70.title: How can Ispot false information?
70.content:
False information can usually be easily told apart from the truth. How can this be done?

Titles

Misinformation websites usually use titles containing CAPITAL LETTERS accompanied by pictures that have visibly been edited. The titles usually contain words like Revealed, Exclusive, Lie, Finally the truth etc. Be aware of articles with extremely long titles. And does the title even correspond with the whole article?

Name of the author

The name of the author is usually missing on most misinformation websites. You can also rarely find any information on the editorial staff. If the author does not sign their name by their article, there isn'tany reason to believe them.

Sources, sources, sources

Does the article cite its sources? Are they trustworthy? Verify them in search engines.

Date

Look at the date of when the article was released. Articles that are many years old and out of date are often shared and they try to make the impression that they somehow related to current affairs.

71.title: Theatre, film and other artistic performances
71.content:
Rules and recommendations

Theatre, film and other artistic performances including circuses and variety shows can no longer take place for the public. Scheduled performances must be moved or cancelled.

It is virtually impossible to operate for cinemas.In fact, the presence of any audience is banned,this applies for both indoors and outdoors shows.

Rehearsals in theatres without the presence of the public may take place. Exceptions from the obligation to wear aface mask apply to artists who are performing on stage - ie actors, singers and dancers. Moderators, editors or other persons appearing on the radio or television do not have to wear aface mask. However, it is always necessary to not exceed the limit of 5singers indoors. The reason is that singing is very risky in terms of the spread of the virus as there is alarge spread of droplets.

72.title: Caregiversallowance for self-employed II
72.content:
Taking care of afamily member for CZK 400 / day for the period fromNovember 10th untilNovember 31st, 2020.

Taking care of afamily member for CZK 400 / day for the period from

Validity
Applications are accepted from November 9th untilDecember 9th, 2020.

Program Rules
The program is intended for self-employed people who are looking after children up to 10 years of age, dependent children up to 26 years of age and dependent individuals on at least level 1of dependency.

The money is intended only for the self-employed with self-employment as their main activity, therefore:

  • the partners of ltd., joint-stock company, limited partnership or public company cannot apply
  • the recipients of parental allowance and people living with the recipient of parental allowance in the same household cannot apply
  • the recipients of the maternity cash benefit and people living with the recipient of the maternity cash benefit in the same household cannot apply
  • the pension recipients (invalidity, widow's, old-age) who are self-employed as their side activity cannot apply
  • nor those who pursue self-employment only as their side activity due to looking after adisabled person.

The care-giversallowance for the self-employed cannot be combined with the Compensation Bonus, which will be paid by the Ministry of Finance.

Application

  1. Confirmation of the closure of aschool or other facility will not be required, this will be required only in justified cases by arequest sent to the applicant.
  2. You can submit your application through the MIT form at: www.mpo.cz/osetrovneosvc
  3. In-person submissions are not possible for hygienic reasons. Applications submitted by the data box are preferred - it will be paid out much earlier.

73.title: Mode of operation
73.content:
Rules and recommendations

Restaurants, pubs, bars and clubs are now closed. Restaurant gardens are also closed. However, from 5AMto 10:59PM it is possible to have an open takeout window and sell takeaway food. Food deliveries can work all day.

The exception is restaurants that are not for the public - these are typically employee canteens or catering providers of health and social services (e.g.canteens in sick, elderly homes) or prisons. The second exception are the restaurants in accommodation facilities, which provide food to their guests (e.g.breakfast for hotel guests) these can operate from 5AMto 10:59PM.

Drinking alcohol is prohibited in the area of restaurant establishments, their surroundings and in all public places (e.g.parks, stops, housing estates, squares, shops, etc.).

When you are buying takeaway food, have your mouth and nose covered at all times, keep at least 2meters of distance from other customers and restaurant staff, use disinfectant and prefer card payment. The more we protect ourselves, the sooner we can go back to eating in restaurants.

74.title: Accommodations
74.content:
Rules and recommendations

The operation of hotels and other accommodation services is presently limited. Accommodation services can be provided only for:

  • business-related purposes (business trips),
  • individuals who have been ordered with work duty,
  • individuals who have been ordered to stay in quarantine or self-isolation,
  • foreigners before their departure from the Czech Republic,
  • foreigners with valid work permit in the Czech Republic.

Private and recreational stays are not possible at present.

It is mandatory to wear aface mask in all public areas of any open accommodation service. Please pay increased attention to all hygienic rules and leave your hotel room only when necessary.

Hotel staff is obliged to carry out complete disinfection of the whole area regularly (especially door handles, halls, railings, elevators, toilets, etc.). It is also vital to take extra care to clean the rooms and handle towels and bedding in an appropriate way. These measures are designed to significantly lower the risk of infection for both staff and clients. By retaining all these high hygienic standards, we will be able to get sooner back to the normal.

Hotel restaurants are exempt from the general ban on the presence of the public in the restaurants. This exemption applies only for hotel guests. Hotel restaurants are granted to open from 5:00 to 22:59.

75.title: Caregiversallowance for full-time employees/people with work agreements
75.content:
The employers can claim the caregiver'sallowance in the amount of 70% of the daily assessment basis, which must be at least CZK 400 per day on full-time employment.

Validity
Applications should be submitted for the previous month (from October 5th, 2020). You can start submitting applications from November 2nd, 2020. If the lockdown continues in November, you will then submit anew application for November.

Program Rules
For the allowance can apply an employee (including those in part-time work agreements, if the health insurance was paid out of the agreement in the month of entitlement or in the previous 3months) who is unable to work due to nursing/care of:

  • Achild under 10 years of age (at the time of entitlement to caregiver'sallowance, the child must be under 10 years of age).
  • Achild (up to the age of 26) in schooling who is dependent on the care of another person (from primary school onwards).
  • An individual older than 10 years dependent on the care of another person using the services of daily, weekly hospitals, and similar facilities.
  • Achild who is unable to attend classes due to family quarantine regulations. These conditions also apply to single parents.

The applicant will receive the money for the relevant month retrospectively. Payment is sent to the same account used for wage payment or by postal order when the wage is paid in cash.

Entitlement to the caregiver'sallowance applies throughout the whole school closure period. However, the right expires upon termination of employment.

Application
You can fill out the application online.
More information about the program.

76.title: Outside seating, terraces, indoor gardens
76.content:
Rules and recommendation

Gardens, terraces and winter gardens are not allowed to operate at the moment. The general ban on the presence of the public in restaurants apply to them. Restaurants are allowed to serve only as atakeout service. It is also possible to get food delivered.

Gathering of people is prohibited in front of the restaurants. Except for household members it is necessary to keep adistance of at least 2meters. We recommend you to eat your meal at home or in the office rather than in acrowded place in front of the restaurant. By following the increased hygienic measures and being considerate, we will be able to return to the restaurant gardens even sooner.

78.title: Compensation bonus
78.content:
Compensation bonus

Applicants can claim the CZK 500 bonus for each day of the immediate ban or restriction of business due to government regulations within the first bonus period from October 5th, 2020 untilNovember 4th, 2020,the second bonus period from November 5th until November 21st, 2020 and the third bonus period from November 22nd, 2020 until December 13th, 2020.

Program Terms
1) The condition for drawing this bonus is the predominant activity in the business, which was directly closed due to government restrictions. Compared to the spring bonus program, the concurrence with employment will no longer be examined. The only thing examined will be the so-called dominant source of livelihood for the decisive period from June 1st until September 30th, 2020in some of the areas affected by government restrictions, such as hospitality, culture, sports and others.

Examples of eligible applicants for acompensation bonus of CZK 500 per day.

2) In addition to the directly affected owners of bars, restaurants or fitness centres, this bonus is also aimed at activities directly related. These include self-employed individuals and partners of small ltd., who are in direct symbiosis with closed areas of the economy and who cannot easily replace their income. For example acoach in the gym or an actor in the theatre. Akey condition for these applicants the inability to supply products or services or to carry out activities. Their work performance must have been reduced by at least 80% (in comparison to the relevant period from June to September 2020). At the same time, this activity must be the main livelihood income for the supplier (or entrepreneur in direct symbiosis), for which there is no easy substitute.

3) People with work agreements: The condition for entitlement to the bonus is that the applicant has worked for at least 3of 4months in the relevant period (from June 1st untilSeptember 30th, 2020) on the insured agreement (from which sickness insurance is paid). I.e.the income for the agreement of the working activity (DP) was at least 3,000 CZK per month, for work agreements (DPP) then over 10,000 CZK per month.

For the bonus can apply self-employed individuals with an active license as of October 5th, 2020 or with ashort-term interruption after March 12th, 2020. In the case of ltd., it must have amaximum of two partners, or it must be afamily ltd.

At the same time, it is impossible to combine this bonus with other direct programs: for example Covid - Culture, Covid - Sport or Caregiver'sallowance for self-employed II.

Application
You can apply in person at the tax office or through data box, but also by e-mail, which was used by about 60% of all applicants in the spring. You can also send it by mail or use online application. The law enters into forceon November 12th, 2020.

More details about the application can be found on the Financial Administration website.

79.title: Weddings
79.content:
Rules and recommendations

Weddings are allowed to happen. There can be amaximum of 20people present, including the couple, the officiator and the registrar.

The wedding reception cannot be held in arestaurant or other catering facilities. The general ban on the presence of the public in restaurants applies. You can meet with your loved ones after the wedding ceremony for example at home. Follow the general rules related to free movement and hygienic regulations, even during the consuming of food and the toast.

During the ceremony, there is an exception from the obligation to wear aface mask. You have to put your mask back on once the ceremony is over. You can only take it off for the necessary amount of time when taking aphoto.

Weddings are allowed to happen but there is alimited amount of guests and it is necessary to follow all hygienic regulations. It is up to you whether you want to get married now or wait until abetter epidemiological situation. Once the risk of infection is lower, these rules will be less strict and you will be able to get married with more guests, abigger celebration and live music.
